<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-inverse-of-2-by-2-matrices-ii" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Inverse of 2 by 2 Matrices II</title>

    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.7 Matrices I
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Determine the inverse of a 2 by 2 matrix</li>
                              <li>Solve linear equations in two unknowns using matrix method</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Teaching Idea</title>
                <p>
                    This Learner Experience uses productive failure and guided discovery. Students first try to invent the inverse formula by reverse-engineering a matrix that undoes another matrix. The point is not that every pair succeeds immediately, but that their attempts create a need for the formula and make its pieces meaningful.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Do not give the formula at the start. Instead, keep students anchored on the equation <m>AX=I</m>. Prompt them to multiply matrices entry by entry, notice that the two columns of <m>X</m> can be solved separately, and connect each part of the final formula to a step in the algebra.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Materials Needed</title>
                <p>One printed activity sheet per pair, pens or pencils, and board space for collecting student findings.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <title>The Undo Machine</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In arithmetic, every number has an undo. Multiplying by <m>3</m> can be undone by multiplying by <m>\frac{1}{3}</m>. Their product is <m>1</m>, the do-nothing number.
            </p>
            <p>
                Matrices have the same idea. The identity matrix <m>I</m> is the do-nothing matrix. A matrix's inverse is its undo. In this activity, you will figure out what that undo matrix looks like and why the formula works.
            </p>
            <p>
                We want to solve
                <me>
                    A A^{-1}=I, \qquad \text{that is} \qquad
                    \begin{bmatrix}a &amp; b \\ c &amp; d\end{bmatrix}
                    \begin{bmatrix}e &amp; f \\ g &amp; h\end{bmatrix}
                    =
                    \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix}.
                </me>
                Your job is to find <m>e</m>, <m>f</m>, <m>g</m>, and <m>h</m> in terms of <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="undo-machine-specific-case">
        <title>Part 1: Warm-up with a Specific Case</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Work with your partner. Let
                <me>A=\begin{bmatrix}2 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp; 4\end{bmatrix}.</me>
                We want to find a mystery matrix
                <me>X=\begin{bmatrix}e &amp; f \\ g &amp; h\end{bmatrix}</me>
                so that <m>AX=I</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                That means
                <me>
                    \begin{bmatrix}2 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp; 4\end{bmatrix}
                    \begin{bmatrix}e &amp; f \\ g &amp; h\end{bmatrix}
                    =
                    \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix}.
                </me>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Multiply out the left side. You will get four expressions, one for each entry of the result.</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                \begin{bmatrix}2e+3g &amp; 2f+3h \\ e+4g &amp; f+4h\end{bmatrix}
                                =
                                \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix}.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Notice that the left column of <m>X</m>, which contains <m>e</m> and <m>g</m>, and the right column of <m>X</m>, which contains <m>f</m> and <m>h</m>, can be solved separately. Write out the two systems of equations.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            Left column:
                            <me>2e+3g=1, \qquad e+4g=0.</me>
                            Right column:
                            <me>2f+3h=0, \qquad f+4h=1.</me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Solve each system using substitution, elimination, or another method you know.</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            From the left column, <m>e=\frac{4}{5}</m> and <m>g=-\frac{1}{5}</m>. From the right column, <m>f=-\frac{3}{5}</m> and <m>h=\frac{2}{5}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Write down your mystery matrix <m>X</m>. Then verify it works by computing <m>AX</m>.</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                X=\begin{bmatrix}\frac{4}{5} &amp; -\frac{3}{5} \\ -\frac{1}{5} &amp; \frac{2}{5}\end{bmatrix}
                                =\frac{1}{5}\begin{bmatrix}4 &amp; -3 \\ -1 &amp; 2\end{bmatrix}.
                            </me>
                            Multiplying <m>AX</m> gives the identity matrix.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                <em>Check-in:</em> compare your matrix <m>X</m> with another pair before moving on.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="undo-machine-spot-pattern">
        <title>Part 2: Spot the Pattern</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Now repeat the same process for these two matrices:
                <me>
                    B=\begin{bmatrix}5 &amp; 2 \\ 3 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
                    C=\begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 0 \\ 2 &amp; 3\end{bmatrix}.
                </me>
                For each matrix, solve <m>AX=I</m> to find <m>X</m>.
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Record the values of <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m> for each matrix.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Write the inverse you found for each matrix.</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                A^{-1}=\frac{1}{5}\begin{bmatrix}4 &amp; -3 \\ -1 &amp; 2\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
                                B^{-1}=\frac{1}{-1}\begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; -2 \\ -3 &amp; 5\end{bmatrix}
                                =\begin{bmatrix}-1 &amp; 2 \\ 3 &amp; -5\end{bmatrix},
                            </me>
                            <me>
                                C^{-1}=\frac{1}{3}\begin{bmatrix}3 &amp; 0 \\ -2 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix}
                                =\begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 0 \\ -\frac{2}{3} &amp; \frac{1}{3}\end{bmatrix}.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Look at the top-left and bottom-right entries of each inverse. What do you notice?</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>The diagonal entries appear to come from swapping <m>a</m> and <m>d</m>.</p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Look at the top-right and bottom-left entries. What do you notice?</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>The off-diagonal entries appear to become <m>-b</m> and <m>-c</m>.</p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Look at the denominators. Can you express the denominator using <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m>?</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>The denominator is <m>ad-bc</m>.</p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <activity xml:id="undo-machine-general-formula">
        <title>Part 3: Derive the General Formula</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Now derive the formula in general. Let
                <me>
                    A=\begin{bmatrix}a &amp; b \\ c &amp; d\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
                    X=\begin{bmatrix}e &amp; f \\ g &amp; h\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
                    AX=I.
                </me>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Write out the four equations you get from <m>AX=I</m>.</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                ae+bg=1, \quad af+bh=0, \quad ce+dg=0, \quad cf+dh=1.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Solve for <m>e</m> and <m>g</m> from the left-column system. Use elimination.</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            The left-column system is
                            <me>ae+bg=1, \qquad ce+dg=0.</me>
                            Eliminate <m>g</m> by multiplying the first equation by <m>d</m> and the second by <m>b</m>:
                            <me>ade+bdg=d, \qquad bce+bdg=0.</me>
                            Subtract to get <m>(ad-bc)e=d</m>, so <m>e=\frac{d}{ad-bc}</m>. A similar elimination gives <m>g=\frac{-c}{ad-bc}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Solve for <m>f</m> and <m>h</m> from the right-column system.</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            The right-column system is
                            <me>af+bh=0, \qquad cf+dh=1.</me>
                            Solving gives <m>f=\frac{-b}{ad-bc}</m> and <m>h=\frac{a}{ad-bc}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>What expression keeps appearing in every denominator?</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p><m>ad-bc</m></p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Write the inverse of <m>A</m> as a single formula.</p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                A^{-1}=\frac{1}{ad-bc}\begin{bmatrix}d &amp; -b \\ -c &amp; a\end{bmatrix}, \qquad \text{where } ad-bc\neq 0.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Whole-Class Consolidation</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>7 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Ask two or three pairs to share what they found. Then write the formula inverse formula.
                    Ask, <q>Where did this come from? Which step in your algebra gave you this?</q>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Key Questions</title>
                <p>
                    Ask, <q>What happens if <m>ad - bc</m> equals zero? What would that mean in your system of equations?</q> Let students suggest ideas such as no unique solution or parallel equations, then connect this to the idea of a non-invertible matrix.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Mnemonic</title>
                <p>
                    Introduce <em>Swap, Negate, Divide</em> only after the derivation: swap the diagonal entries, negate the off-diagonal entries, and divide by <m>ad-bc</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    <insight>
        <p>
            The formula for the inverse of the 2 by 2 matrix <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\ c \amp d\end{bmatrix}</m> is:
            <md>
                A^{-1} = \frac{1}{ad-bc}\begin{bmatrix}d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}
            </md>
            This only exists if <m>ad - bc \neq 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            You can remember this formula by the mnemonic <em>Swap, Negate, Divide</em>: 
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Swap</title>
                    <p>
                        Swap the positions of the diagonal entries <m>a</m> and <m>d</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Negate</title>
                    <p>
                        Negate the off-diagonal entries <m>b</m> and <m>c</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Divide</title>
                    <p>
                        Divide each entry by <m>ad-bc</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Your friend used a matrix to encode a secret message. She multiplied a vector of numbers by the matrix
                <me>M=\begin{bmatrix}3 &amp; 1 \\ 5 &amp; 2\end{bmatrix}</me>
                to scramble it. After encoding, she got the message vector
                <me>\begin{bmatrix}11 \\ 19\end{bmatrix}.</me>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Find <m>M^{-1}</m> using your new formula.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Use <m>M^{-1}</m> to decode the message by computing <m>M^{-1}\begin{bmatrix}11 \\ 19\end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>What was the original vector?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Extension: Could she have chosen any encoding matrix? What would go wrong if she chose <m>\begin{bmatrix}2 &amp; 4 \\ 1 &amp; 2\end{bmatrix}</m>?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\det(M)=3(2)-1(5)=1</m>, so
                        <md>M^{-1}=\begin{bmatrix}2 &amp; -1 \\ -5 &amp; 3\end{bmatrix}.</md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \begin{bmatrix}2 &amp; -1 \\ -5 &amp; 3\end{bmatrix}
                            \begin{bmatrix}11 \\ 19\end{bmatrix}
                            =
                            \begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 2\end{bmatrix}.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The original vector was <m>\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 2\end{bmatrix}</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        No. This matrix has <m>ad - bc = 2(2)-4(1)=0</m>, so it has no inverse. If a matrix has no inverse, there is no reliable undo step for decoding.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 12 \end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Find <m>A^{-1}</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>If <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y\end{bmatrix}</m>, solve <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m> using the inverse.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p> Applying the formula,
                        <md>
                            <mrow> A^{-1} 
                            \amp = \frac{1}{(2)(2) - (1)(3)} \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ -3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ -3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p> Since <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m>, we can left multiply by <m>A^{-1}</m> to get <m>\mathbf{x} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b}</m>. So:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \mathbf{x} \amp = A^{-1}\mathbf{b} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ -3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 12 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Hence <m>x = 2</m> and <m>y = 3</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve the system <m>2x - y = 1</m> and <m>3x + 2y = 14</m> using the inverse method.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Write the system as
                <md>
                    <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ 3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 14 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                </md>
                The inverse is
                <md>
                    <mrow> A^{-1} = \frac{1}{(2)(2) - (-1)(3)} \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ -3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{7} \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ -3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                </md>
                Therefore,
                <md>
                    <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = A^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 14 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                </md>
                So <m>x = 2</m> and <m>y = 4</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A community theatre in Kisumu sells adult and student tickets. Two student tickets and three adult tickets cost KSh <m>1800</m>. Five student tickets and two adult tickets cost KSh <m>2300</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                We need to find the cost of one adult ticket and one student ticket.
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Let <m>x</m> be the cost of one student ticket and <m>y</m> be the cost of one adult ticket. Write the system of equations.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Write the system in matrix form and find the inverse of the coefficient matrix.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Use the inverse to solve for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The system is
                        <md>
                            <mrow> 2x + 3y = 1800 </mrow>
                            <mrow> 5x + 2y = 2300 </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In matrix form,
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 3 \\ 5 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1800 \\ 2300 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                        The inverse of the coefficient matrix is
                        <md>
                            <mrow> A^{-1} \amp = \frac{1}{(2)(2) - (3)(5)} \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -3 \\ -5 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{11} \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -3 \\ -5 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{2}{11} &amp; \tfrac{3}{11} \\ \tfrac{5}{11} &amp; -\tfrac{2}{11} \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Therefore,
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = A^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 1800 \\ 2300 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{2}{11} &amp; \tfrac{3}{11} \\ \tfrac{5}{11} &amp; -\tfrac{2}{11} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1800 \\ 2300 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 300 \\ 400 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                        So a student ticket costs KSh <m>300</m> and an adult ticket costs KSh <m>400</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the inverse of <m>M = \begin{bmatrix} -1 &amp; 4 \\ 2 &amp; 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> M^{-1} 
                        \amp = \frac{1}{(-1)(5) - (4)(2)} \begin{bmatrix} 5 &amp; -4 \\ -2 &amp; -1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{13} \begin{bmatrix} 5 &amp; -4 \\ -2 &amp; -1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{5}{13} &amp; \tfrac{4}{13} \\ \tfrac{2}{13} &amp; \tfrac{1}{13} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the inverse of each matrix, if it exists.</p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 5 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 4 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; -2 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 \\ 2 &amp; 4 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>D = \begin{bmatrix} -3 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 5 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>E = \begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; 1 \\ -1 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>F = \begin{bmatrix} -2 &amp; 3 \\ 1 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 &amp; -1 \\ -5 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>B^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{4} &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; -\tfrac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>No inverse, since <m>\det{C} = 0</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>D^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{1}{3} &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; \tfrac{1}{5} \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>E^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ 1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>F^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{1}{5} &amp; \tfrac{3}{5} \\ \tfrac{1}{5} &amp; \tfrac{2}{5} \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the inverse of each matrix, if it exists.</p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 7 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; -4 \\ 2 &amp; 5 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>C = \begin{bmatrix} -4 &amp; -1 \\ 2 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>D = \begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; -2 \\ 5 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>E = \begin{bmatrix} -1 &amp; 2 \\ 3 &amp; -6 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>F = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -3 \\ 1 &amp; 4 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{7} &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; \tfrac{1}{3} \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>B^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{5}{13} &amp; \tfrac{4}{13} \\ -\tfrac{2}{13} &amp; \tfrac{1}{13} \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>C^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; \tfrac{1}{2} \\ -1 &amp; -2 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>       
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>D^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{10} &amp; \tfrac{1}{5} \\ -\tfrac{1}{2} &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>No inverse, since <m>\det{E} = 0</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>F^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{4}{11} &amp; \tfrac{3}{11} \\ -\tfrac{1}{11} &amp; \tfrac{2}{11} \end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A printing kiosk in Nairobi charges for black-and-white pages and colour pages. A student prints 3 black-and-white pages and 2 colour pages for KSh <m>110</m>. Another student prints 5 black-and-white pages and 1 colour page for KSh <m>125</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    We need to find the cost of one black-and-white page and the cost of one colour page.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>Let <m>x</m> be the cost of one black-and-white page and <m>y</m> be the cost of one colour page. Write the system of equations.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Write the system in matrix form and find the inverse of the coefficient matrix.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Use the inverse to solve for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The system is
                            <md>
                                <mrow> 3x + 2y = 110 </mrow>
                                <mrow> 5x + y = 125 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            In matrix form,
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} 3 &amp; 2 \\ 5 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 110 \\ 125 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                            </md>
                            The inverse of the coefficient matrix is
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A^{-1} \amp = \frac{1}{(3)(1) - (2)(5)} \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; -2 \\ -5 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{7} \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; -2 \\ -5 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{1}{7} &amp; \tfrac{2}{7} \\ \tfrac{5}{7} &amp; -\tfrac{3}{7} \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Therefore,
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = A^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 110 \\ 125 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{1}{7} &amp; \tfrac{2}{7} \\ \tfrac{5}{7} &amp; -\tfrac{3}{7} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 110 \\ 125 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 20 \\ 25 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                            </md>
                            So a black-and-white page costs KSh <m>20</m> and a colour page costs KSh <m>25</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A school bookshop sells notebooks and pens. Two notebooks and three pens cost KSh <m>480</m>, while five notebooks and one pen cost KSh <m>680</m>. Find the cost of one notebook and one pen using the matrix inverse method.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The system is
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 2x + 3y = 480 </mrow>
                        <mrow> 5x + y = 680 </mrow>
                    </md>
                    so
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 3 \\ 5 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 480 \\ 680 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                    </md>
                    The inverse is
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A^{-1} = \frac{1}{(2)(1) - (3)(5)} \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; -3 \\ -5 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} = -\frac{1}{13} \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; -3 \\ -5 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Hence
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = A^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 480 \\ 680 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 120 \\ 80 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                    </md>
                    So a notebook costs KSh <m>120</m> and a pen costs KSh <m>80</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A museum in Nairobi sells tourist and local tickets. Three tourist tickets and four local tickets cost KSh <m>2300</m>, while two tourist tickets and five local tickets cost KSh <m>2000</m>. Use the inverse method to find the cost of each ticket type.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The system is
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 3x + 4y = 2300 </mrow>
                        <mrow> 2x + 5y = 2000 </mrow>
                    </md>
                    so
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} 3 &amp; 4 \\ 2 &amp; 5 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2300 \\ 2000 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                    </md>
                    The inverse is
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A^{-1} = \frac{1}{(3)(5) - (4)(2)} \begin{bmatrix} 5 &amp; -4 \\ -2 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{7} \begin{bmatrix} 5 &amp; -4 \\ -2 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Therefore,
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = A^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 2300 \\ 2000 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp =  \frac{1}{7} \begin{bmatrix} 5 &amp; -4 \\ -2 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 2300 \\ 2000 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 500 \\ 200 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                    </md>
                    So a tourist ticket costs KSh <m>500</m> and a local ticket costs KSh <m>200</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <title>Inverse of the Product of Matrices</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 \\ 3 &amp; 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>Find <m>A^{-1}</m> and <m>B^{-1}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Compute <m>AB</m> and <m>(AB)^{-1}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Find <m>A^{-1}B^{-1}</m>, the product of the inverses. Is it equal to <m>(AB)^{-1}</m>? </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Instead, find <m>B^{-1}A^{-1}</m>, the product of the inverses in the opposite order. Is it equal to <m>(AB)^{-1}</m>?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>If <m>C</m> is any invertible <m>2\times 2</m> matrix, write a guess for the formula for <m>(ABC)^{-1}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Computing <m>A^{-1}</m> first:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A^{-1} 
                                \amp = \frac{1}{(1)(4) - (2)(3)} \begin{bmatrix} 4 &amp; -2 \\ -3 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{2} \begin{bmatrix} 4 &amp; -2 \\ -3 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -2 &amp; 1 \\ \tfrac{3}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Now for <m>B^{-1} </m>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> B^{-1} 
                                \amp = \frac{1}{(2)(3) - (1)(0)} \begin{bmatrix} 3 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{6} \begin{bmatrix} 3 &amp; -1 \\ 0 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{1}{6} \\ 0 &amp; \tfrac{1}{3} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Finding the matrix product:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> AB \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 \\ 3 &amp; 4 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 7 \\ 6 &amp; 15 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Taking the inverse:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> (AB)^{-1} 
                                \amp = \frac{1}{(2)(15) - (7)(6)} \begin{bmatrix} 15 &amp; -7 \\ -6 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{12} \begin{bmatrix} 15 &amp; -7 \\ -6 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{5}{4} &amp; \tfrac{7}{12} \\ \tfrac{1}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{1}{6} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Multiplying the inverses in the same order as the original matrices:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A^{-1}B^{-1} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -2 &amp; 1 \\ \tfrac{3}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{1}{6} \\ 0 &amp; \tfrac{1}{3} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -1 &amp; \tfrac{2}{3} \\ \tfrac{3}{4} &amp; -\tfrac{5}{12} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            </md>
                            This is not the same as <m>(AB)^{-1}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Multiplying the inverses in the opposite order:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> B^{-1}A^{-1} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{1}{6} \\ 0 &amp; \tfrac{1}{3} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} -2 &amp; 1 \\ \tfrac{3}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{5}{4} &amp; \tfrac{7}{12} \\ \tfrac{1}{2} &amp; -\tfrac{1}{6} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Hence <m>(AB)^{-1} = B^{-1}A^{-1}</m>.
                        </p>
                        <note>
                            <p>
                                Why is the order reversed? Think about <m>A</m> representing putting your shoes on, and <m>B</m> representing putting your socks on. <m>AB</m> represents putting on your socks and then your shoes. To undo this, we must first take off our shoes, <m>A^{-1}</m>, and then take off our socks, <m>B^{-1}</m>, which is <m>B^{-1}A^{-1}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Taking the inverse of a product inverts the order of the matrices, so we guess that <me>(ABC)^{-1} = C^{-1}B^{-1}A^{-1}</me>
                            Try to confirm this by choosing a specific <m>C</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <title>Inverse of Diagonal Matrices</title>
            <statement>   
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>M = \begin{bmatrix}5 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; -2\end{bmatrix}</m>. Find <m>M^{-1}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>N = \begin{bmatrix}a &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; b\end{bmatrix}</m> be a diagonal matrix with entries <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>. Prove that <me>N^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{a} &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; \frac{1}{b}\end{bmatrix}</me>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>   
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the formula for the inverse of a 2 by 2 matrix, we have
                            <md>
                                <mrow> M^{-1} \amp = \frac{1}{(5)(-2) - (0)(0)} \begin{bmatrix}-2 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 5\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{-10} \begin{bmatrix}-2 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 5\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}\frac{-2}{-10} &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; \frac{5}{-10}\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{5} &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; -\frac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the formula for the inverse of a 2 by 2 matrix, we have
                            <md>
                                <mrow> N^{-1} \amp = \frac{1}{(a)(b) - (0)(0)} \begin{bmatrix}b &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; a\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{ab} \begin{bmatrix}b &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; a\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{a} &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; \frac{1}{b}\end{bmatrix}  </mrow>
                            </md>
                            as required.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>             
        </exercise>        
    </exercises>

